From t.w at aggiemail.usu.edu  Fri Apr  6 21:26:50 2012
From: t.w at aggiemail.usu.edu (Tammy Wilson)
Date: Fri, 6 Apr 2012 11:26:50 -0800
Subject: [R-sig-eco] How to calculate geographical coordinates of
 sampling points following (by bearing and distance) a georeferenced one?
In-Reply-To: <CAAVnHssYhiDHVpoBiDwC3u1KqTtQPA5uf_nDx6vcZeFGk5V6rA@mail.gmail.com>
References: <CAAVnHssYhiDHVpoBiDwC3u1KqTtQPA5uf_nDx6vcZeFGk5V6rA@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAFeE-bJKCYxSASfESzSD_741gFR7LgjySUzz+x8sB1osRszpGg@mail.gmail.com>

Trigonometry will work for projected coordinate systems like UTM:

Try this:
# number of points
n = 30

# reference location
ref.pt = cbind(1,2)

# generate some random directions
# This can be your list of your bearings converted to radians
dir <- runif(n,0,2*pi )

# generate some random distances
# This can be your list of distances in map units (e.g. m)
dist <- runif(n,0.5,10)

#empty matrix for coordinates
coords.mat = cbind(rep(0,n),rep(0,n))

#using trigonometry to calculate object location
for (i in 1:n){
              coords.mat[i,1] = ref.pt[1]+(sin(dir[i])*dist[i])
              coords.mat[i,2] = ref.pt[2]+(cos(dir[i])*dist[i])
        }
plot (coords.mat)
points(ref.pt,col=2)

Best,
Tammy


